Anonymous Sat 20 Nov 2021 00:50:29 No.43316787 Report
Quoted By: >>43317897
Reposting my feedback for Winter's Crawl from the write thread. Context: >>43023261

Character death may play a part in many horrors, but with the given plot and writing style killing someone off would feel cheap and unwarranted. Horror novels use death to give weight to a villain and source a sense of dread to the surviving cast that it could happen to them, but in this story it's unnecessary. Roberta, for example, could be injured, scared off, or isolated from Dominic to achieve the same fear-inducing outcome without the nasty moral considerations murder adds to a character we see through their eyes, even if that character is a literal monster.

If you're committed to the horror angle, you could try instilling fear that's already present but unused. A monster stalking you is spooky, so give some hints to the humans beyond mundane speculation such as footprints that don't quite look like a bear or claw marks too big for any bird. They're too cozy in their homes, so cut the power and sabotage the cars so they can't leave for help. There's a big spooky forest outside that Dominic could be lured/dragged into that taps into primal fears of darkness, isolation, and the unknown.

Giving insight into the mind of the person being spooked always works, and you've done it before in other works. The final scene from entirety Dominic's perspective would be horrifying, what with being chased inside your own home. Maybe he would connect the dots too late, realizing the motive of his stalker in the end. Maybe he would hastily retreat behind a bear-proof door, only to realize that his pursuer knows how to turn a knob. You already have a protagonist we can care about, but it's up to you communicate his terror to us( ex. nightmares, cold sweat, pounding heart).

This way you can use horror(erotic horror?) elements to enhance your brilliant characterization.

Again, just offering suggestions. Hope you found this helpful.

No problem, I visit here too.

>was there something specific about my writing style that made it seem cheap and unwarranted?
Your writing style tends to prioritize characters and their unique perspectives. Much of the story concerns the human's personal lives, putting readers right into their shoes. Because of this, killing Roberta as an established character would only serve as shock value to readers. All the characterization you built up with her and Dominic would be greatly diminished as well. You have already demonstrated the Owl's willingness to kill through this murder attempt and her slaughter of woodland animals, so the point got across. It's only because there ended up being a witness present (Dominic) during the attempt on Roberta's life that the Owl relented, but this showcased an important boundary that the Owl didn't cross. If the Owl did actually kill Roberta, it would make it extremely difficult to empathize with her actions. In the wild animals rarely fight to the death over mates, instead opting for less lethal ways to demonstrate dominance. If the Owl were to kill in self-defense or due to provocation however, that could contribute to the story in a meaningful manner.

As for likeability, I think that it's part of the appeal of stories like these to challenge preconceived notions for an inhuman being. A language barrier, fear factor, or initial hostility would limit reader understanding. You got around these barriers by telling the story through the Owl's eyes, giving us a distinctly inhuman, yet still relatable viewpoint. This worked great because we now know that the Owl is capable of rational thought and fears yet still demonstrates her bestial side through impulsive and reckless acts. This desire for intimacy serves as motivation for her rash actions, something that could be understood if given enough time. It's that small inkling of hope that things could work out despite the odds which drive this unconventional love story.
